{"type":"text","timestamp":1775879275642,"sessionID":"ses_28559b781ffeNc94rCoz90JPV3","part":{"id":"prt_d7aa70096001IiaDqLBv1kwyd1","messageID":"msg_d7aa6ed3f001WdT51zdy6PxVAO","sessionID":"ses_28559b781ffeNc94rCoz90JPV3","type":"text","text":"The file already contains a different proposal. I'll overwrite it with the correct AR-029 proposal.","time":{"start":1775879275639,"end":1775879275639}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775879275721,"sessionID":"ses_28559b781ffeNc94rCoz90JPV3","part":{"id":"prt_d7aa7447b001TiRoiQHXnioJi7","messageID":"msg_d7aa6ed3f001WdT51zdy6PxVAO","sessionID":"ses_28559b781ffeNc94rCoz90JPV3","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_tool-e58d2dd910f44c39bb8cf3546d9124ab","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# Proposal: AR-029 — SDK HTTP 底层客户端\n\n## Purpose\n\nAR-029 aims to implement and standardize the HTTP client layer for the AgentCube Python SDK. This layer provides the underlying HTTP communication infrastructure for:\n- Control plane operations (session creation/deletion via Workload Manager)\n- Data plane operations for Code Interpreter (command execution, file operations)\n- Data plane operations for Agent Runtime (payload invocation)\n\nThe HTTP client layer ensures consistent request/response handling, connection pooling, timeout management, and session header management across all SDK clients.\n\n## Scope\n\n### In Scope\n1. **Control Plane Client (`ControlPlaneClient`)**\n   - HTTP client for Workload Manager interactions\n   - Session lifecycle: create and delete Code Interpreter sessions\n   - Authentication via Bearer token (auth_token argument or K8s SA token file)\n   - Connection pooling with configurable pool settings\n\n2. **Code Interpreter Data Plane Client (`CodeInterpreterDataPlaneClient`)**\n   - HTTP client for Router-based Code Interpreter operations\n   - Command execution (shell commands, code execution)\n   - File operations: write, upload, download, list\n   - Session header: `x-agentcube-session-id`\n   - Base URL construction from router_url + namespace + cr_name\n\n3. **Agent Runtime Data Plane Client (`AgentRuntimeDataPlaneClient`)**\n   - HTTP client for Router-based Agent Runtime operations\n   - Session bootstrapping via GET on invocation endpoint\n   - Payload invocation via POST\n   - Session header: `x-agentcube-session-id`\n   - Base URL construction from router_url + namespace + agent_name\n\n4. **HTTP Session Utilities**\n   - `create_session()`: Creates `requests.Session` with connection pooling\n   - `read_token_from_file()`: Reads auth token from K8s SA token path\n   - Timeout configuration: default read timeout 120s, connect timeout 5.0s\n\n5. **Exception Hierarchy**\n   - Base exception: `AgentCubeError`\n   - `CommandExecutionError`: For non-zero exit codes\n   - `SessionError`: For session management failures\n   - `DataPlaneError`: For data plane operation failures\n\n### Out of Scope\n- High-level client logic (context managers, retry policies, automatic reconnection)\n- WebSocket or streaming communication\n- API version negotiation beyond v1 paths\n- TLS/certificate configuration beyond default `requests` behavior\n\n## Impact Analysis\n\n### Positive Impact\n1. **Consistency**: Single HTTP client implementation pattern across all SDK clients\n2. **Performance**: Connection pooling reduces connection overhead\n3. **Reliability**: Configurable timeouts prevent hanging requests\n4. **Maintainability**: Centralized HTTP logic makes updates easier\n5. **Testing**: Clear separation allows mocking HTTP clients in tests\n\n### Dependencies\n- `requests` library (>= 3.0)\n- `PyJWT` (>= 2.0.0)\n- `cryptography`\n- Python >= 3.10\n\n### Breaking Changes\nNone. This is a new module implementation.\n\n### Compatibility\n- Backward compatible with existing SDK public API (`CodeInterpreterClient`, `AgentRuntimeClient`)\n- Environment variables: `WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL`, `ROUTER_URL` for default configuration\n- K8s SA token path: `/var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount/token`\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### Alternative 1: Use `httpx` instead of `requests`\n**Pros**:\n- Async support built-in\n- HTTP/2 support\n- Modern API design\n\n**Cons**:\n- Additional dependency\n- Less mature ecosystem compared to requests\n- Would require learning curve for maintainers\n\n**Decision**: Stick with `requests` due to maturity and broader adoption in Python ecosystem.\n\n### Alternative 2: Separate configuration dataclass for HTTP settings\n**Pros**:\n- Centralized configuration management\n- Easier to override defaults consistently\n\n**Cons**:\n- Adds indirection and complexity\n- Current per-client constructor approach is simpler\n- No clear benefit for the limited number of HTTP settings\n\n**Decision**: Keep configuration distributed across client constructors for simplicity and explicitness.\n\n### Alternative 3: Auto-retry on transient failures\n**Pros**:\n- Improved resilience in production environments\n- Handles temporary network issues\n\n**Cons**:\n- Adds complexity to HTTP client layer\n- Retry logic is application-specific\n- Could mask underlying issues\n\n**Decision**: Defer retry logic to higher-level clients or application code; keep HTTP layer simple and predictable.\n\n## Implementation Plan\n\n### Phase 1: Core HTTP Utilities\n- Implement `create_session()` with connection pooling\n- Implement `read_token_from_file()`\n- Implement exception hierarchy\n\n### Phase 2: Control Plane Client\n- Implement `ControlPlaneClient` with Workload Manager endpoints\n- Add auth token resolution (argument → K8s SA token → none)\n- Implement `create_session()` and `delete_session()`\n\n### Phase 3: Code Interpreter Data Plane Client\n- Implement base URL construction logic\n- Implement all file operations (write, upload, download, list)\n- Implement command execution with timeout handling\n- Add session header management\n\n### Phase 4: Agent Runtime Data Plane Client\n- Implement session bootstrapping via GET\n- Implement `invoke()` with POST payload\n- Add session header management\n\n### Phase 5: Integration\n- Update `CodeInterpreterClient` to use new HTTP clients\n- Update `AgentRuntimeClient` to use new HTTP clients\n- Add unit tests for all HTTP clients\n- Add integration tests with mock servers\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n1. All HTTP clients pass unit tests with 100% coverage\n2. Integration tests demonstrate successful:\n   - Session creation and deletion via Control Plane\n   - Code execution and file operations via Code Interpreter Data Plane\n   - Agent invocation via Agent Runtime Data Plane\n3. No breaking changes to public API\n4. Documentation updated for new HTTP client classes\n5. Performance benchmarks show connection pooling reduces overhead","filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/proposal.md"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/proposal.md","exists":true,"truncated":false},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775879275653,"end":1775879275718}}}}
